node.text: Sue Bird (@sbird10), 40, has assumed the role of wizened veteran, both on and off the court. Now the WNBA’s all-time assists leader, Bird will bring her extraordinary floor vision to the Tokyo Olympics, where she and teammate Diana Taurasi hope to become the first basketball players to win five Olympic gold medals.

node.text: @allysonfelix's fifth return to the Olympics was delayed by the COVID-19 pandemic. She talks to TIME about her decision to still pursue the games, what it was like to train with her family during lockdown, and how she hopes to inspire her daughter.

node.text:
When Terrance Franklin was shot to death in a Minneapolis basement eight years ago, the only witnesses were the five police officers assembled to capture him. Two of them were bleeding—wounded by rounds from a police submachine gun the department declared the young Black man had managed to get control of in a brief struggle, a contest it said ended with Franklin’s death in a fusillade of immediate return fire. The officer who gave the most detailed account said the fatal encounter lasted “seconds.” 

Franklin’s death was briefly a major story in the Twin Cities but nowhere else, not least because it was a story told by the police alone, write Karl Vick and Josiah Bates. On May 10, 2013, there was no body-camera footage that his skeptical family could demand be released, and no demands on the nightly news for an impartial inquiry. The Minneapolis Police Department investigated its own officers and concluded they had heroically taken down a would-be cop killer. 

But there was a video, and it suggests a different story. 

Franklin’s family called his killing an “assassination.” During the course of TIME’s reporting, prosecutor Michael Freeman asked the Minnesota Bureau of Criminal Apprehension to investigate the tape and other “new evidence” in the Franklin case.

Watch TIME’s documentary by @francescatrianni, and read the full article: https://time.com/6075094/terrance-franklin-shooting/

node.text: @anthonyramosofficial will be introduced to millions when @intheheightsmovie, one of this summer’s most anticipated blockbusters, premieres in theaters and on HBO Max on June 11. The Warner Bros. film, directed by Jon M. Chu and adapted from Lin-Manuel Miranda's and Quiara Alegría Hudes' Tony-winning 2008 musical about a community bursting with culture and drama in upper Manhattan, represents a full-circle moment for Ramos. It's a neighborhood story that conjures his own upbringing. It's the show that, when he saw it as a teen, convinced him he had a place in a theater world sorely lacking in Latino representation, writes Andrew R. Chow. And it sees Ramos stepping into the shoes of his mentor Miranda, who was meant to play the lead role of Usnavi—a hardluck bodega owner with dreams of returning to the Dominican Republic—a decade ago, before the film slipped into development hell. The battles Miranda and others fought in that time resulted in a moment in which a face like Ramos' can be that of a leading man's—and Ramos hopes to do the same for a new generation. Ramos is part of TIME's newest class of Next Generation Leaders. Read the full cover story: https://ti.me/3vdXJ6P Photograph by @jingyulin_ for TIME; video by Dorotea Sotirovska, Joey Lautrup, Erica Solano and Isaiah King

node.text: @amandascgorman captivated the world when she read her poem “The Hill We Climb” at President Joe Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris’ Jan. 20 Inauguration ceremony. “I don’t think I always knew I was going to be the Inaugural poet, but every single time I wrote a public poem, before I began writing it, I would tell myself: write a poem that is worthy of a presidential inauguration,” Gorman says in a video interview shot during her cover shoot. Sitting just feet away from the 22-year-old on Inauguration Day was former First Lady @michelleobama—who had met Gorman twice before. In a remote interview, the two covered topics ranging from the role of art in activism to the pressures Black women face in the spotlight. Read their full conversation at the link in bio. Video by @spencerbakalar, @paulmoakley, @adamperez22 and Rose Cohn (@rosepwn) for TIME

node.text: The challenges of the past year and a half have transformed our world, and few industries have been as affected as travel, tourism and hospitality. In many ways, our third annual list of the World's Greatest Places is a tribute to the people and businesses at the forefront of those industries who, amid extraordinary circumstances, found ways to adapt, build and innovate. It shines a light on ingenuity, creativity, revitalization and reopenings in 100 unique destinations across the world. While it may not be possible to safely visit each place just yet, they’re all well worth reading (and dreaming) about until it's time, once again, to explore. Read more, and see the full list, at the link in bio. Map by Katherine Baxter (@baxmaps) for TIME; animation by @brobeldesign

node.text: Tucker Carlson has strengthened his hold on the conservative mind at a moment when most of the right's elected leaders have been dethroned. The Senate's top Republican, Mitch McConnell, has lost the GOP majority there, House Minority Leader Kevin McCarthy is fumbling to corral a fragmented caucus, and Donald Trump has lost both the White House and his social media megaphone. When correspondent @charlottealter asked Carlson why Republicans had lost their grip on the federal government, he was unsparing. "First of all, they're inept and bad at governing," he said. "The party is much more effective as an oppositional force than it is as a governing party." Culture has supplanted policy as the central organizing principle of American conservatism, and Carlson—photographed on the set of his daytime show, Tucker Carlson Today, which launched in May—has emerged as the leader of that oppositional force. Read more at the link in bio. Photograph by @gigilaub for TIME

node.text: In the days since Zaila Avant-garde's historic Scripps National Spelling Bee win on July 8, it's become clear that the teen from a suburb of New Orleans who displays her spelling prowess, and what she can do with three basketballs, on morning TV shows is also a thoughtful girl capable of her own baby-voiced social analysis, writes Janell Ross. She knows she earned her victory, and with it a place in history (as the first Black American to win and hold the title of national spelling bee champion, which comes with a $50,000 prize). That's something to celebrate. But she also seems entirely aware, at 14, that the American gospel that hard work can get you anything is more myth than reality. Read more at the link in bio. Photograph by @scottymacphoto—@nytimes/@reduxpictures

node.text: Win Htet Oo, born in Malaysia to Burmese parents, says he was taught to be proud of his Burmese heritage. Representing Myanmar at the Olympics was his goal and would have been the "pinnacle" of his two-decade swimming career. "It wasn't just to say I swam at the Olympics," Win Htet Oo tells TIME via video call from Melbourne, Australia, where he lives and trains. "It was to show Myanmar that we could get to the Olympics if we had the right training, if we had the right coaches, the right facilities." But after the Feb. 1 military coup that overthrew the democratically elected government in Myanmar, he forfeited his chance at Olympic glory, saying he would not represent the military junta in international competition. Now, the 27-year-old is criticizing the International Olympic Committee for allowing the military government to send a delegation to Tokyo—saying the organization's policy of neutrality risks tarnishing the core values of the Olympic Games. By boycotting the Tokyo Games, Win Htet Oo, photographed during a training session on April 29, is effectively putting an end to his swimming career that started when he was six years old, writes Aria Chen. But, he says, he doesn't regret it. "I stand in solidarity with so many people in Myanmar, whose dreams have also fallen apart," he says. "My sporting career is nothing compared to everything that they've lost." Read more at the link in bio. Photograph by Asanka Brendon Ratnayake (@abrfoto)—@afpphoto/@gettyimages

node.text: In 2007, as Beijing was preparing to host the Olympics for the first time, Dhondup Wangchen picked up his camera and crisscrossed Tibet, emboldened by the government promises to protect human rights and press freedom that helped secure its bid. Wangchen gathered 40 hours of interview footage from 108 Tibetans discussing the upcoming Games, the Dalai Lama, political persecution and Han migration. The 24-minute film he produced, Leaving Fear Behind, landed him six years in a squalid prison, where he was "tortured day and night and kept in solitary confinement for over 86 days," he tells TIME from exile in San Francisco. "China broke every one of its promises." Today, Beijing is preparing to host the Olympics once again, further burnishing its image, though this time on its own terms. China no longer makes pledges to respect human rights according to international definitions, and secured the Winter Games without vowing to protect its minorities. Wangchen says any country participating at Beijing 2022 "will further embolden the CCP [Chinese Communist Party] to commit all kinds of crimes against humanity without any consequences or accountability." Read more about how Beijing is redefining what it means to be Chinese, from Xinjiang to Inner Mongolia, at the link in bio. Photograph by Carolyn Drake (@drakeycake)—@magnumphotos for TIME

node.text: "When I was very young, I was like, 'oh, I'm a boy. I just am,'" @leo_baker recalls of his childhood. For years, Baker tells TIME, he put questions about his gender on hold as he grew a successful career as a skateboarder, going on to win a series of international skateboarding competitions, including the Street League Super Crown in 2016. But the thoughts never went away and, at the age of 19, Baker realized he was trans. "It was two different worlds, and for a decade, my life was splintered as I was trying to figure out what I was doing," he says of the divide between his private life and public image. Now 29, Baker is embracing both his gender identity and his passion for skating freely, after resigning from the U.S. Women's Olympic Skateboarding Team and transitioning publicly last year. "I couldn't keep putting myself on hold," he says. In losing out on his shot at the Tokyo Olympics, Baker found himself. Read more at the link in bio. Photograph by @ethanjamesgreen for TIME

node.text: Street artist @akse_p19 repairs the mural of Manchester United striker and England soccer player @marcusrashford on the wall of the Coffee House Cafe in Withington on July 13. The mural had been defaced with graffiti after England lost the Euro 2020 final to Italy, but was subsequently covered with messages of support by well wishers. Rashford, Jadon Sancho and Bukayo Saka—three Black players on England's squad who each failed to score in the penalty shootout at the end of the game—were racially abused on Twitter and Instagram following the team's defeat. Why, even after public warnings, are social media platforms still struggling to stamp out racist abuse faster than it appears—and what it might take to fix the problem? Read more at the link in bio. node.text: As West Virginia's most populous county, with about 180,000 residents living across roughly 900 sq. mi., Kanawha has logically reported the state's highest raw numbers of COVID-19 cases (more than 15,500) and deaths (359), but its case rate is much lower than those in many nearby counties. Kanawha has also been remarkably successful at vaccinating quickly and broadly. Indeed, Kanawha County officials' collaborative health-delivery model, intimate understanding of their community and willingness to meet people where they are could help rewrite the textbook for public health in the post-pandemic age, writes Jamie Ducharme. If that model is followed, the big business of health care may turn into something smaller, more localized—and hopefully better equipped to keep us all well. Read more at the link in bio. In this photograph: Dana Campbell plays 'You Are My Sunshine' on the harmonica before being vaccinated in his home in Elkview in June. With demand for COVID-19 vaccines slowing, health officials in Kanawha County have been making house calls. Photograph by @rebecca_kiger for TIME

node.text: In July 2017, Gulzira Auelkhan's father fell ill. So she made the short hop from her village in the windswept Kazakhstan countryside into her native China to care for him. Upon arrival in the western province of Xinjiang, however, she was arrested, for no given reason. No charges were ever brought, writes Charlie Campbell, but she spent the next 15 months being ferried between five different prison camps with barbed wire and watchtowers, during which she was interrogated 19 times and tortured with electric batons. Her interrogators had no clear explanation for her detention. Auelkhan, 42, an ethnic Kazakh Muslim who grew up speaking a Turkic dialect, was forced to learn Mandarin Chinese, salute the Chinese flag and sing songs exulting the Chinese Communist Party beneath photos of President Xi Jinping. "We all had to eat pork, and I was forced to burn a Koran and a prayer mat," says Auelkhan, who is now based in the U.S. "There was to be no more praying." Afterward, she was sent to a labor camp for two months, where she sewed gloves until she says her neck ached and her eyes turned bloodshot. Camp guards told detainees that "from now, all ethnicities will be as one and must share the same language and food," she says. Life for Xinjiang’s Muslim minorities—mostly Uighurs but also Kyrgyz, Uzbeks and Kazakhs like Auelkhan—is a daily grind of surveillance, indoctrination and detention. Read more about how Beijing is redefining what it means to be Chinese, from Xinjiang to Inner Mongolia, at the link in bio. Photograph by @farahkhad for TIME

node.text: Flames crawl along a utility pole as the Sugar Fire, part of the Beckwourth Complex Fire, tears through central Doyle, Calif., on July 10. The Beckwourth Complex Fire, comprised of two lightning-caused fires that are burning near the border with Nevada, has become California's largest wildfire of the year, the Associated Press reports. The Sugar Fire exploded in recent days as another heat wave brought triple-digit temperatures to the region. On Sunday morning, a Plumas National Forest incident report said the footprint of the Beckwourth Complex Fire had reached 83,926 acres, or about 131 square miles, and was 8% contained.
